metadata.name: Forgotten Memories #64
metadata.description:
Memories can be dark or they can be bright. Sometimes they are faint and pale, sometimes they are vivid and colorful. Sometimes they are hard to forget, sometimes they are easy to remember.

Memories are easily interrupted or even fractured, but they are also mostly always connected with other memories, whether they are related or not.

Forgotten Memories is what I consider to be my most ambitious study of color harmony yet. Each color represents a different category of memory, which are stored in our mind in layers of time. Their shapes differ in width and length depending on how weak/strong the memory was and how long it lasted.

Once a memory is forgotten, it may or may never be remembered again. But one thing that is not to be forgotten is that whether we choose to forget or remember, we are made of our memories.

* * *

Press S to save as PNG.
Press 1 to save with 1000px height.
Press 2 to save with 2000px height.

Made by: yenren / twitter.com/yenrenART
License: LICENSE.txt

metadata.name: Whisper #188
metadata.description:
Abstract forms built with noise and texture

-------------

A note on rendering times: *Whisper has a lot going on*. It can take up to 1-5 minutes to fully render, depending on your hardware configuration, including a 15sec-1min loading phase during which lots of calculations take place (but no visuals). It'll get there, just be patient! A small loading bar along the bottom also shows the progression of the render during the drawing phase.

Press 'S' or click "Save image" to save a PNG version of the artwork while in full-screen/IPFS view

Customisation
-------------

The following parameters can be adjusted in full-screen mode.
Open the token in full-screen/IPFS mode, and add any of these to the URL:

&size=2000 (replace 2000 with any value up to around 8000) - this sets the resolution/width of the canvas in pixels. Use this to generate very large PNG images (50MB+) suitable for printing at large DPI & canvas sizes. The max value here is dependent on your hardware, might not work on mobiles etc.

&ratio=1.4 (any value between 1 and 2, default = 1.4) - set the aspect ratio of the work. By default Whisper renders at 1:1.4 but you can change this to match other printing formats. Different ratios will produce slightly different outputs, but the overall character of the artwork should still be present. Landscape mode is not supported.

metadata.name: pang #280
metadata.description:
Within each of us resides an evolutionary history of primal emotions, yet we often spend our lives dulling and controlling these instincts rather than reveling in them. Art is one of the ways we best express those instincts and intuitions – accessing and visualizing their visceral qualities, and releasing our deepest emotions in a way we can share.

pang reflects emotions that take control of our impulses – anguish, euphoria, obsession. By using crayon-like marks, the artworks convey the catharsis felt while drawing with a childlike abandon. To capture what gives such marks true feeling, the works deliberate the intrinsic movements, pressures, and angles shaped by hands in various moods. These qualities and their frenetic meanderings represent the infinite possibilities of where the crayon could go next – if only we could free ourselves from the layers of control we've built.

The contradictions we struggle with are reflected throughout the works:  in the long, methodical, and mathematical path to creation that yields work that looks fast, free and unrehearsed;  through the randomly-informed computer generation of art that feels human;  and by the depiction of long-standing traditional techniques to help display the conceptual range of a young, innovative art movement still establishing its pivotal place in the canon of art. These tensions parallel the work's underlying concept, accentuating the suspicion that a learned fear of emotional expression might just be the source of our own pang. 

Created in p5.js, pang is inspired by the emotional works and processes of later abstract expressionists such as Cy Twombly and Joan Mitchell – as well as contemporary artists like José Parla.

Functionality: 
Press ‘p’ to save as a png. 
Press ‘b’ to render with (or without) a transparent background.
Press 0-9 to render at varying degrees of quality.  0 (lowest quality) to 9 (highest quality, 15000 pixels lengthwise).
Press ⬆️ (arrow up) to incrementally increase pixel density.
Press ⬇️ (arrow down) to incrementally decrease pixel density.

__________
TENDER x abstractment
April 2022

metadata.name: Intangible #145
metadata.description:
Let me take you places. Those are not in your town, not even on your planet. They’re placed somewhere between reality and subconsciousness.
Enormous, peculiar structures emerge upon you, refusing to be ignored. They are your unfulfilled cravings or ever-lurking demons. They were always there, under your skin, intangible, now they’ve materialized.
You may not like them, they may seem too vast, too scary to tame. But ultimately, you have to face them, unless you enjoy living in their shadow. 

___
Inspirations

I’ve never truly realized that, but ever since I remember, the sight of gigantic objects or creatures evoked strong emotions within me.
It probably started with playing Shadow of Colossus (a video game) as a kid and seeing The Cathedral (short movie by Tomasz Bagiński). Years later, reading Solaris (by Stanisław Lem) aroused the same feeling (among others) of being mesmerized by the vastness. More recently, movies like Denis Villeneuve’s Arrival (which also nudged my attraction to mystery) and Dune - have charmed me.

Earlier this year I have stumbled across Dawid Planeta (artist and yoga teacher) and began contemplating his visions of mini people in the jungle inhabited by giant animals. These works in particular, plus Hollow - generative series by Jacek Markusiewicz - were probably my final inspirations to make Intangible look the way it does.

Settling semi-random generative structures in some kind of reality, gave them a meaning - they may symbolize things much bigger than you - the ones you try to escape from or those you’ve been longing to experience for years. I have mine, don’t you?

___
Controls in live mode


Keyboard
[ space ] - toggle light animation
[ S ] - save image with current size (default is 120% of browser window’s height; you may change browser’s scale or check URL size param)
[ F ] - fullscreen 
[ up / down ] - light intensity
[ left / right ] - base light position
[ 1..5 ] - aspect ratio: 10:16 („zero” ratio), 1:1.4142 (vertical A4), 1:1, 1.4142 (horizontal A4), 16:10
[ B ] - toggle border
[ Z ] - toggle canvas „raw” mode - no shadow / margin (auto applied in fullscreen mode)
[ N ] - toggle „that thing you may not want on print”


URL params
You may add any number of parameters to the URL to start it with particular settings. 
[ animate ] (1/0) - toggle light animation
[ size] (number) - number of px for longer edge, i.e. 4000
[ ratio ] (number or ratio with format: 10/16, 10:16, 10_16) - aspect ratio
[ light ] (number 40..120, some palettes have slightly different limits for good results) - light intensity
[ lightShift] (number -100..100) - base light position
[ border ] (1/0) - toggle border
[ hddcy ] (0/1)

Example: [ &size=4000&border=1&light=100&animate=1 ] 


Mobile
[hold 2 fingers for 2s] - save
[double tap] - fullscreen


___
Note:
I encourage you to do some light adjustments before you save an image for print. I’m pretty sure you can do better than fxrand().


___
Special thanks to my brother Krzycho, for lots of advices / heathy criticism and to Olga, for never-ending excitement and „dorady”.

___
Developed in Javascript, using p5.js (2D Canvas) and chroma.js.

metadata.name: Holy Moly #37
metadata.description:
The idea for this project came from a common drawing exercise where different shapes and shading are used to create the illusion of depth. Here I'm using four layers containing various types of holes. Some are recognizable primitive shapes but others are organic in form or distorted. There are ten features reported that affect the character of each output.

2. Use the keys 2-8 to change resolution, '2' will produce a 2000 x 2000 image (default), '3' a 3000 x 3000 image etc
3. Once generated press 'S' to save as a png

metadata.name: Dopamine Dreams #25
metadata.description:
Dopamine is a chemical released in the brain that makes you feel good.

Dopamine Dreams is an exploration of using patterns and geometric forms to create something that also makes you feel good; to create something that feels natural, as if it has sprung from the ground or appeared in the sky.  

In this work, there is a conversation happening between two modes for drawing the same grid. One is tight, geometric and calm. The other is loose, loopy and excited. They overlap, interlace and compete to fill the space.  One cannot exist without the other. Balance is the the key. Between them they create a landscape in which to dream. 

Generative artwork by AutoEclectus

Controls in live mode:
- After animation stops, press [s] to save a png

@autoeclectus everywhere - Twitter, Instagram and Masterdon. 
https://autoeclectus.art

metadata.name: Cell.estials [Adam.Atom] #2
metadata.description:
---------------------------
"Human beings are members of a whole, In creation of one essence and soul."
- Saadi Shirazi, Persian Poet, 14 A.D.

---------------------------
We all share a divinity at heart while we each have our own unique beauty. we are made out of cosmic energies that transmute celestial elements into material existence which holds all of us together like the atoms of a body, while each one of us is itself a cell within a larger body of universe.

Each piece reflects you - a celestial cell floating in space - a microcosm consisting of a soul (point at center) surrounded by other souls (atoms of the body) that live in the macrocosm of our world, within or without our borders.

The circular composition made out of circular points is intended to resemble the fractal attribute of the cosmos, where all elements (stars, planets, atoms) are either an insignificant point or a large body of an entity - solely depending on the eye of the observer.

The concentric geometric pattern at the center represents a motif known as Shamseh in Islamic arts and architecture (similar to Mandala in other Sacred arts) symbolizing the divine unity behind the multiplicity of all that is created. 

------- CONTROLS -------
Press [+] to increate the dot size
Press [-] to decrease the dot size
Press [0] to reset the dot size to default

Press [t] to toggle the poem text visibility
Press [i] to change the poem text size
Press [o] to change the poem text color
Press [p] to change the poem text placement [Bottom | Top]

Press [r] to switch between canvas ratios [Square | Landscape | Portrait]

Press [1] to save in base resolution [1280x1280 | 1280x720 | 960x1280]
Press [2] to save in 1.5x resolution [1920x1920 | 1920x1080 | 1440x1920]
Press [3] to save in 2x resolution [2560x2560 | 2560x1440 | 1920x2560] *
Press [4] to save in 3x resolution [3840x3840 | 3840x2160 | 2880x3840] *
Press [5] to save in 4x resolution [5120x5120 | 5120x2880 | 3840x5120] *
Press [6] to save in 5x resolution [6400x6400 | 6400x3600 | 4800x6400] *
Press [s] to save in current resolution

* Rendering takes longer time as resolution increases.
* For rendering high density outputs, it is recommended to consider smaller dot size (using controllers mentioned) for a better detailed look.

metadata.name: Sunburst #13
metadata.description:
"Sunburst" is a homage to Kenneth Noland, created in the artist's signature style and colors. Simple geometric shapes - circles, squares, and triangles - are arranged in a dynamic and rhythmic composition. The bold, bright colors of yellow, red, blue, and brown are applied in thin, translucent layers, creating a relationship between form and color, as well as the interplay between the different shapes and hues. The circles, squares, and triangles appear to float and dance across the surface of the canvas, creating a sense of movement and energy. At the same time, the subtle variations in color and texture create a sense of depth and complexity, inviting the viewer to linger and explore the work further.

Click [s] to save a PNG file.
